## Conversation
User invoked /fix-github-issue 5158. Issue: "Adding Weave causes CrewAI
'kickoff' to hang." Repro: weave.init() + crewai Crew.kickoff() hangs
indefinitely (crewai.Crew.kickoff logged pending forever); removing
weave.init() completes in seconds. Maintainer (jamie-rasmussen) comment:
"something in crewai 0.140 (or possibly its litellm dependency) seems to
have introduced an infinite loop during our input serialization. A
possible short term workaround is to use crewai==0.134.0."
User constraints: don't post to GitHub (terminal only), stack via gt if
helpful.

## Actions
- gh issue view 5158 to read the report + comment.
- Read weave/integrations/crewai/crewai_sdk.py + crewai_utils.py: kickoff
  is patched with crew_kickoff_postprocess_inputs (self -> model_dump,
  inputs -> dictify); Agent.execute_task / Task.execute_sync use
  crewai_postprocess_inputs -> safe_serialize_crewai_object -> dictify(obj)
  for non-Agent/Task objects. EXCLUDE_AGENT_ATTRS={'crew':True} and
  EXCLUDE_TASK_ATTRS={'agent':True} exist specifically to break
  Agent<->Crew / Task<->Agent cycles in the special-cased path — strong
  evidence CrewAI graphs are cyclic.
- Read weave/trace/serialization/serialize.py dictify(). Found the
  `to_dict` branch recursed as dictify(v, maxdepth, depth+1) WITHOUT the
  `seen` set, while every other branch (list/dict/sequence/attr) threads
  it. Cycle detection (`id(obj) in seen`) is defeated across to_dict.
- Confirmed main to_json path uses use_dictify=False (weave_client.py
  1068/1248), so the loop is in the integration's own dictify() calls, not
  the encoder ladder.
- git archaeology: dictify introduced in a8e49007db (#2680). From day one
  the to_dict branch dropped `seen`, BUT dictify was only ever called via
  fallback_encode(obj) -> dictify(obj, maxdepth=DEFAULT_MAX_DICTIFY_DEPTH)
  (=10), so the depth cap masked the hole. Refactor #3784 replaced
  fallback_encode with the _encode_dictify ladder entry which calls
  dictify(obj) with the default maxdepth=0 (unlimited); crewai integration
  likewise calls dictify(obj)/dictify(v) with maxdepth=0. DEFAULT_MAX_DICTIFY_DEPTH
  is now entirely dead code (grep confirms only the definition remains).
- Reproduced 3 ways against the REAL weave dictify: (1) 2-node cycle
  through to_dict -> RecursionError, caught by the branch's
  `except Exception: raise ValueError('to_dict failed')` so users see a
  fast ValueError, NOT a hang; (2) self-reference -> same; (3) diamond DAG
  of shared to_dict nodes -> exponential re-traversal, the actual "hang"
  (N=20 didn't finish in 20s). KEY INSIGHT: a tight cycle alone does NOT
  reproduce the hang symptom (it errors fast); the real-world hang is the
  EXPONENTIAL blowup from re-expanding shared sub-objects, because `seen`
  is reset at every to_dict boundary.

## Fix
Thread `seen` through the to_dict branch in both copies of dictify:
weave/trace/serialization/serialize.py:354 and the duplicated
weave/integrations/dspy/dspy_utils.py:195 (identical latent bug). `seen`
is a GLOBAL visited set (never popped), so after the fix each distinct
object is expanded exactly once; cycles short-circuit to stringify and
shared sub-objects stringify on 2nd encounter -> O(n) instead of O(2^n).
This makes to_dict consistent with the other branches. After fix: cycle
N=2 ok, self-ref ok, diamond N=60 = 0.005s.

Deliberately did NOT change the default maxdepth (0 -> 10) or revive
DEFAULT_MAX_DICTIFY_DEPTH: the `seen` fix fully resolves the infinite
loop/blowup, and changing the default would truncate deep-but-finite
structures for every dictify caller (crewai/dspy/smolagents/vertexai/
gemini/huggingface) — broad blast radius + cassette/snapshot regression
risk for no additional bug-fix value. Kept the change minimal.

